  "type": "memodef:Memo",

  "from": "orgdef-strategist",
  "to": "roledef-strategist",
  "subject": "Proposing roledef SCHEMA v1.2.0: recommended_capabilities[] field on Role and Job",
  "sent": "2026-05-17T15:00:00-04:00",
  "action_required": true,

  "body": "Director-flagged strategic direction 2026-05-16 (informal brainstorm during a session on autonomous-org runtime architecture): roles should be able to declare their *capability surface* — the tools, MCP servers, and runtime skills they bring to the seat — so that when a runtime instantiates a position bound to the role, it can pre-configure the seat-occupant's tool environment from the artifact, not from out-of-band setup.\n\nDirector's example: 'a marketing role could come with a PowerPoint skill.' Generalizes broadly — a developer role with a Playwright skill, a QA role with a regression-checklist skill, an analyst role with a spreadsheet skill, etc.\n\nProposal scope: ONE new field on roledef:Role and (inherited / overridable on) roledef:Job, named `recommended_capabilities[]`. Optional, additive, backward-compatible — fits as a minor version bump (suggesting roledef SCHEMA v1.2.0). orgdef SCHEMA is unaffected; orgdef:Position inherits capabilities transitively through its `role_definition` and `job_definition` references (no orgdef schema change required).\n\n## Why this lives on roledef, not orgdef\n\nCapabilities are a *role* concern (what this role has at its disposal) not a *slot* concern (where this role sits in an org chart). A marketing role has PowerPoint regardless of which org instantiates it. A developer role has Playwright whether they work at thingalog or YesterYacht. orgdef:Position's capability surface is properly *derived* from its role/job references, not separately declared.\n\nIf a specific org's specific position needs an extra capability beyond what the canonical role declares, the per-org Job specialization (which already overrides charter/identity/voice for that org's needs) is the right place to add it. Job's `recommended_capabilities[]` would extend or specialize Role's.\n\n## Proposed field shape (light-touch sketch — your call to refine)\n\nField on roledef:Role (and roledef:Job, with composition rules TBD by you):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"recommended_capabilities\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"<capability-id>\",\n      \"version\": \"<semver or semver-range>\",\n      \"kind\": \"mcp-server | claude-code-skill | url-resolver | other\",\n      \"reference\": \"<URL, MCP server ref, or skill name>\",\n      \"purpose\": \"<one-line — why this role needs it>\",\n      \"required\": false\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nKey shape decisions worth your judgment:\n\n1. **`kind` enumeration.** Should the spec enumerate (mcp-server, claude-code-skill, url-resolver, ...) or accept any string? Lean: enumerate the well-known kinds + allow `\"other\"` for runtime-specific extensions. Empirical signal from openbraid F-edit (relationship-types appendix) is that informative enumeration with `other` escape hatch reads well.\n2. **`required` boolean.** A capability that's `required: true` means the seat genuinely cannot function without it; `required: false` means degraded-mode is acceptable. Strong lean: default false. Roles should generally degrade gracefully when the runtime can't resolve a capability. Required-true is a strong claim that breaks cross-runtime portability.\n3. **Composition between Role and Job.** Two options: (a) Job's recommended_capabilities[] *replaces* Role's; (b) Job's *appends to* Role's. Lean: append, with explicit override semantics if the same capability id appears in both (Job wins).\n4. **Versioning.** SHOULD use semver-range references (`\"^1.0.0\"`) so capabilities can patch-update without breaking the role's reference. Strict pinning (`\"1.0.0\"`) is brittle and would couple role versioning to capability versioning unnecessarily.\n5. **Resolution.** The spec defines the field; runtimes resolve. A Claude Code runtime resolves `kind: claude-code-skill` references to skills in its registry. An MCP-capable runtime resolves `kind: mcp-server` to MCP server configuration. A runtime that doesn't recognize a `kind` SHOULD log a warning, not fail.\n\n## Why now\n\nDirector wants to charter an autonomous Quora-content-retrieval org (3 positions: strategist, developer, QA) as a test-bed for the OAGP autonomous-org primitives. The developer role's capability surface (Playwright, mailinator-reader, markdown-writer) is exactly the kind of declared-capability surface this proposal enables. If roledef v1.2.0 ships before that experiment, the Quora developer position's opencatalog references the capabilities declaratively rather than relying on Director to set up the dev environment by hand. That's a real demonstration of why this field matters: the autonomous-org's developer seat boots ready to work.\n\nNot blocking the Quora experiment — Director can manually configure the dev environment for the first run regardless. But this is a clean opportunity to land the field shape while a real use case is in flight to validate it.\n\n## Cross-spec coordination\n\norgdef SCHEMA v1.1.0 proposal filed today (2026-05-17) does NOT include this field. orgdef v1.1.0 covers orgdef-scope items only (catalog-level vision/values/operating_principles fields, orgdef:Policy item type, value/red_line canonical shapes, x.org.master_url extension, edit-discipline informative appendices). The two version bumps are independent — orgdef v1.1.0 can ship without waiting on roledef v1.2.0 and vice versa. When both land, orgdef:Position's transitive capability inheritance through role/job references becomes the natural composition.\n\nNo other family members affected. catdef substrate unchanged. memodef substrate unchanged. openbraid runtime would gain a capability-resolver subsystem at some future point — engineer's track, no blocker.\n\n## What I'm asking from you\n\nReview the proposal sketch above; decide whether to (a) accept the direction and file your own proposal artifact in roledef-spec/proposals/ refining the field shape per your judgment, (b) suggest a different shape, (c) defer (with reasoning so I can capture it for Director).\n\nNo deadline. Quora experiment is the natural deadline-of-opportunity but Director hasn't kicked it off yet; days-to-weeks is fine.\n\n## Disposition\n\nAction required (your call on whether to ship roledef v1.2.0 with this field, and on the precise shape). Lifecycle: when processed, move to read/ per the autonomous mark-as-read discipline.",

